## Background and Motivation

Blazor server-side rendering (SSR) re-instantiates and re-renders every component subtree on each request. There is no built-in way to cache the rendered output of a component subtree and replay it on subsequent requests without running the child components' lifecycles. Output caching primitives exist at the middleware/endpoint level, but nothing lets an app author declare, *inline in a component tree*, that a specific subtree's HTML should be cached and varied by request dimensions (query, route, header, cookie, user, culture, or a custom key).

This proposal adds the public API surface needed for that: a `CacheBoundary` component that wraps the content to cache and exposes the vary-by and expiration knobs, a `CacheBoundaryLiveComponentAttribute` for component authors to declare that their component must not be baked into cached output (or may be, conditionally, when the boundary varies by given dimensions), a `CacheBoundaryVaryBy` flags enum used by that attribute, and two `RazorComponentsServiceOptions` properties to configure the cache store (size limit and an optional `HybridCache` instance).

PR dotnet/aspnetcore#65772.

## Proposed API

Adds the `CacheBoundary` component plus the supporting attribute, flags enum, and service-options configuration.

```diff
namespace Microsoft.AspNetCore.Components
{
+    public sealed class CacheBoundary : Microsoft.AspNetCore.Components.IComponent, System.IDisposable
+    {
+        public CacheBoundary() { }
+        public Microsoft.AspNetCore.Components.RenderFragment? ChildContent { get; set; }
+        public string? CacheKey { get; set; }
+        public bool Enabled { get; set; }
+        public System.TimeSpan? ExpiresAfter { get; set; }
+        public System.DateTimeOffset? ExpiresOn { get; set; }
+        public System.TimeSpan? ExpiresSliding { get; set; }
+        public string? VaryBy { get; set; }
+        public string? VaryByQuery { get; set; }
+        public string? VaryByRoute { get; set; }
+        public string? VaryByHeader { get; set; }
+        public string? VaryByCookie { get; set; }
+        public bool? VaryByUser { get; set; }
+        public bool? VaryByCulture { get; set; }
+        public void Dispose() { }
+    }

+    [System.AttributeUsage(System.AttributeTargets.Class, AllowMultiple = false, Inherited = true)]
+    public sealed class CacheBoundaryLiveComponentAttribute : System.Attribute
+    {
+        public CacheBoundaryLiveComponentAttribute() { }
+        public bool Disallow { get; set; }
+        public CacheBoundaryVaryBy VaryBy { get; set; }
+    }

+    [System.Flags]
+    public enum CacheBoundaryVaryBy
+    {
+        None = 0,
+        Query = 1,
+        Route = 2,
+        Header = 4,
+        Cookie = 8,
+        User = 16,
+        Culture = 32,
+    }
}

namespace Microsoft.AspNetCore.Components.Endpoints
{
     public sealed class RazorComponentsServiceOptions
     {
+        public long CacheBoundarySizeLimit { get; set; }
+        public HybridCache? CacheBoundaryHybridCache { get; set; }
     }
}
```

## Usage Examples

Cache a subtree and vary the cached output by the `category` query-string value:

```razor
<CacheBoundary VaryByQuery="category" ExpiresAfter="TimeSpan.FromMinutes(5)">
    <ProductList Category="@Category" />
</CacheBoundary>
```

Disambiguate two boundaries under the same parent, and vary by the authenticated user:

```razor
<CacheBoundary CacheKey="sidebar" VaryByUser="true">
    <UserSidebar />
</CacheBoundary>
```

Author a component that must stay live inside a boundary unless the boundary varies by user:

```csharp
[CacheBoundaryLiveComponent(Disallow = true, VaryBy = CacheBoundaryVaryBy.User)]
public class AuthorizeViewCore : ComponentBase
{
    // Cached only when the enclosing CacheBoundary sets VaryByUser="true";
    // otherwise using it inside a CacheBoundary throws.
}
```

Configure the store from `Program.cs` (opt into the `HybridCache`-uses store, and bound the in-memory store size):

```csharp
builder.Services.AddHybridCache(); // auto-selects the HybridCache-uses store
builder.Services.Configure<RazorComponentsServiceOptions>(options =>
{
    options.CacheBoundarySizeLimit = 50 * 1024 * 1024; // 50 MB in-memory limit
    // options.CacheBoundaryHybridCache = mySeparatelyConfiguredHybridCache;
});
```

## Alternative Designs

- **A single `VaryBy` string with an embedded syntax (e.g. `VaryBy="query:category;user"`)** instead of separate `VaryByQuery`/`VaryByRoute`/`VaryByHeader`/`VaryByCookie`/`VaryByUser`/`VaryByCulture` parameters. Rejected because a stringly-typed mini-language is not discoverable, has no compile-time checking, and diverges from the strongly-typed vary-by shape used elsewhere; the flags enum (`CacheBoundaryVaryBy`) is used on the attribute where a compact set is needed, while the component surfaces one parameter per dimension for clarity.
- **A method/service API (e.g. `ICacheBoundary.RenderCached(...)`) or a `[OutputCache]`-style attribute on the component type** instead of a wrapper component. Rejected because the natural authoring model for "cache this subtree" in Blazor is a component that wraps `ChildContent`; a component composes with markup, `@key`, and render-mode boundaries, whereas an attribute or imperative call would not.
- **Three separate expiration types folded into one `CacheExpiration` parameter object** instead of `ExpiresAfter` / `ExpiresOn` / `ExpiresSliding`. Rejected because the flat, nullable `TimeSpan?`/`DateTimeOffset?` parameters mirror existing caching APIs (absolute, absolute-at, sliding) and are simpler to set from Razor markup than constructing an options object.
- **A dedicated cache-store service interface exposed publicly for store selection** instead of the `RazorComponentsServiceOptions.CacheBoundaryHybridCache` property. Rejected in favor of the property because it mirrors the existing circuit-persistence configuration pattern (auto-populated from a registered `HybridCache`, overridable explicitly) and keeps the public surface to a single option.

## Risks

- **`CacheBoundaryLiveComponentAttribute` naming and precedent.** The attribute name mixes two concepts — a "live component" opt-out (`Disallow`) and a conditional cache-inclusion policy (`VaryBy`). It establishes the vocabulary third-party component authors will apply to their own types via `[CacheBoundaryLiveComponent]` and is hard to rename after shipping, so the name should be confirmed.
- **`ExpiresSliding` is not honored by every store.** The parameter exists on `CacheBoundary` but the `HybridCache`-uses store throws `NotSupportedException` for sliding expiration. A parameter that silently only works with one store configuration is an API-shape footgun; consider whether sliding expiration belongs on the common surface.
- **Broad, boolean-and-string mixed vary-by surface.** `VaryByUser`/`VaryByCulture` are `bool?` while `VaryByQuery`/`VaryByRoute`/`VaryByHeader`/`VaryByCookie` are `string?` (comma-separated, with `"*"` meaning "all"). The inconsistency between boolean toggles and string lists, plus the `"*"` sentinel, is easy to misuse and cannot be validated at compile time.
- **`CacheBoundaryVaryBy` flag values are part of the contract.** The enum is `[Flags]` with fixed bit values (`Query=1`…`Culture=32`); the set and their numeric values become a binary-compatibility contract once shipped, so any future dimension must be added as a new bit without reordering.
- **`CacheBoundarySizeLimit` units and edge values.** The limit is a `long` in bytes where `0` disables caching and negatives throw `ArgumentOutOfRangeException`; the units and the meaning of `0` are not evident from the signature and rely on documentation.

